# Build and compat safety

## Compat headers and macros

- **Never bulk-replace** a symbol inside the file that **defines** it (macros, aliases, constexpr wrappers). Exclude compat headers (`*Compat.h`, `*Util.h` macro blocks) from project-wide sed/replace.
- Prefer **`namespace { constexpr auto ... }` + `#define ALIAS ns::value`** over `#define ALIAS Qt::Thing` so a mistaken replace cannot make the macro self-referential.
- After editing a compat header, add or keep a **compile-time smoke check** (e.g. a one-line inline helper that uses the macro/constant) so a broken definition fails in that header, not at random call sites.

## New translation units

- **`dcpp/`** uses `aux_source_directory` — new `*.cpp` files in that directory are picked up on **cmake reconfigure**, not on incremental `make` alone.
- When adding a new `*.cpp` in a globbed directory, still **append it to the explicit `DCPP_EXTRA_SOURCES` list** in `dcpp/CMakeLists.txt` (documents intent; adds missing files if glob is ever removed).
- After adding sources: **re-run cmake** and **build the affected target** before finishing the turn.

## Behavior-preserving security fixes

- Do not drop **fallback paths** (e.g. `getUser` when `findUser` misses) unless the replacement covers the same cases.
- When parsing **untrusted hub text** (status lines, colons, free-form bodies), **validate** extracted fields (nick-like: length, no spaces/control/protocol chars) before acting; use **trusted fields** from structured parsers (chat nick from `<nick>`) without re-parsing the body.
- If validation fails, **return silently** — do not call `stopConnect` / block with a guessed identity.
